document.title: [Archdiocese of Milwaukee Curriculum Documents (Exit Expectations, Gr4)]

64C891C42D034E179D23AD8513E67313.description:
Work cooperatively and respect my classmates’ ideas,
roles and abilities.

E5456C5CB8D44774A88902EE95B7E30D.description:
Demonstrate stewardship inspired by Catholic values
in the care of local and global environments.

BEE5D36E98454A83AC10946128AA6E2A.description:
Describe/compare life from the fossil record with
modern life forms and discuss Biblical implications.

4325DE09188B45BD9EBC63233A481B49.description: Compare how well the solution(s) performed.

25916BD3D7FE40498DC6796B218C40AF.description: Test solution(s) with a range of likely conditions.

C648437878AC4EC19481E879DABE4DE6.description:
Design solutions to reduce the impacts of Earth’s
processes on humans.

599DF5E6292C4C35B719F7F2F66C1278.description:
Testing a solution involves investigating
how well it performs under a range of likely
conditions.

C40E4181DF2F49E18A1DF2E592D02E4C.description:
Humans cannot eliminate the hazards but
can take steps to reduce their impacts.

715A10F12349413DBD41B63CC9EA4B30.description:
A variety of hazards result from natural
processes (e.g. earthquakes, tsunamis,
volcanic eruptions).

C1D0C723CEF4494CACF06AD80FECC6A7.description:
Generate and compare multiple solutions to
reduce the impacts of natural Earth processes on humans.
[Clarification Statement-limited to earthquakes, floods,
tsunamis, and volcanic eruptions}

4C62F3AD5CF64DC6B7E1F5F70139F183.description:
Communicate the harmful effects of obtaining and
using fossil fuels.

BE3B4E95877B4FEE94159BBF3F282089.description:
Provide evidence of how the use of natural resources
affect the environment.

97E4F8D9AE4543E38FF71F2422D9340E.description:
Some resources are renewable over time
and others are not.

41A17F1EA3304B7FA364EFC9D39C25BF.description:
Energy and fuels that humans use are
derived from natural sources, and their use
affects the environment in multiple ways.

CE27FFBE737C4150B23EA3EFA63975D0.description:
Obtain and combine information to describe that
energy and fuels are derived from natural resources and
their uses affect the environment.
[Clarification Statement- Examples of renewable energy
resources could include wind energy, water behind dams,
and sunlight; nonrenewable energy resources are fossil
fuels and fissile materials. Examples of environmental
effects could include loss of habitat due to dams, loss of
habitat due to surface mining, and air pollution from
burning of fossil fuels.

5B9716389E574293B71752ABA7A12033.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth and Human Activity

D6858300735E41E5B3F38911868CCCD4.description:
Analyze and interpret data in order to explain that
Earth’s surface is always changing.

66845B77CDFB48FFAD2BE4E17196BAD9.description:
Explain that features of the Earth’s surface are
constantly changing by a combination of slow and
rapid processes.

9F188337244E470FB078D6B4D272EDA9.description:
Maps can help locate the different land and
water feature areas of Earth.

B507DC58111446C5AF940C84E4A4EAA9.description:
Major mountain chains form inside
continents or near their edges.

D2BFDD3FFAB2469EA773D923BEB745B8.description:
Most earthquakes and volcanoes occur in
bands that are often along the boundaries
between continents and oceans.

91DE9CDB62134918AD4E05212E027DF2.description:
The locations of mountain ranges, deep
ocean trenches, ocean floor structures,
earthquakes, and volcanoes occur in
patterns.

1236DCD8E3A74D2E8A600E8E27D9C6EE.description:
Analyze and interpret data from maps to describe
patterns of Earth’s features.
[Clarification Statement- Maps can include topographic
maps of Earth’s land and ocean floor, as well as maps of
the locations of mountains, continental boundaries,
volcanoes, and earthquakes.]

F9690A8530DB4430A14AB3581700652C.description: Define erosion and the moving of rocks and soil.

89C0C4349C754387A4914FCC594B85C2.description:
Plan and investigate the effects of weathering and
erosion.

FE7F608DD99E4178A302380579CB4ADD.description:
Living things affect the physical
characteristic of their region.

62E1C97ED0DF4720A7EA91DC85873AC7.description:
Water, ice, wind, living organisms, and
gravity break rocks, soil, and sediments into
smaller particles and move them around.

3FD1C61426E64C68B8C1CF7F5F32B97C.description:
Rainfall helps to shape the land and affects
the types of living things found in a region.

C9E0245692D544F3A0F459291110C3CC.description:
Make observations and/or measurement to
provide evidence of the effects of weathering or the rate
of erosion by water, ice, wind or vegetation.
[Clarification Statement- Examples of variables to test
could include angle of slope in the downhill movement of
water, amount of vegetation, speed of wind, relative rate
of deposition, cycles of freezing and thawing of water,
cycles of heating and cooling, and volume of water flow.

A251D2DD5EE64354A28F3B4D581DE2B5.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth’s Systems

1E03E034981E481E968560595422738A.description:
Provide evidence about how landscape has changed
over time.

AB0830A323D34894B097EB1775F1159A.description:
Explain how rocks can change over time as a part of
the rock cycle.

1563C4D698F94AF5A7A76ED504C689C8.description: Identify the three types of rocks.

C9D0830F47F4445E8BE63A292018AAFD.description:
Local, regional, and global patterns of rock
formation reveal changes over time due to
Earth’s forces, such as earthquakes.

F8E580EF2353440BA1989C43CE1275E7.description:
The presence and location of certain fossil
types indicate the order in which rock layers
were formed.

3315A966E0DF4D2ABCA5BF1F10C4F366.description:
Identify evidence from patterns in rock
formations and fossils in rock layers to support an
explanation for changes in landscape over time.
[Clarification Statement- Examples of evidence from
patterns could include rock layers with marine shell fossils
above rock layers with plant fossils and no shells, indicating
a change from land to water over time; and, a canyon with
different rock layers in the walls and a river in the bottom,
indicating that over time a river cut through the rock.]

2468921C84EE40E886143B0CAF2A48A6.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth’s Place in the Universe

1B7B52276B014D36BED6D88DA15330A0.description:
Work cooperatively and respect my classmates’
ideas, roles, and abilities.

D2C54FC339274B8694304AB52C6DD789.description:
Recognize animals obtain information in different
ways.

668C19E0206C4666B4AE3F00B9199C3E.description: Describe an organism’s response to stimuli.

755D17BDBAD44F71A566BDDCBED2543D.description:
Use a model to show how animals receive, process,
and respond to information.

6076188A19784EDE81BAEE0182B58529.description:
Animals are able to use their perceptions and
memories to guide their actions.

C2DECF4C368745D694152CEA95C73FA8.description:
Different sense receptors are specialized for
particular kinds of information.

7B1D04C6D0464D7AB230D077A9498455.description:
Use a model to describe that animals
receive different types of information through their
senses, process the information in their brain, and
respond to the information in different ways.
[Clarification Statement: Emphasis is on systems of
information transfer.]

C720E450F892471FAF7713DC0B5367B9.description:
Construct an argument for the importance of an
organisms structures.

19826557951E4CB29E9F46CCB26FE83E.description:
Identify the parts of a flower and their role in
growth/survival/reproduction

B347F3F20FB24DFC9039966144BB4597.description:
Explain the function(s) of a particular plant or
animal structure

9F6A360B2BE14056AFC7820C11A290AD.description:
Define and identify macroscopic internal and
external structures of plants and animals.

C2C9EE8FE64446DDA630ECDCDE62F03E.description:
Plants and animals have internal and external
structures that serve various functions in growth,
survival, behavior and reproduction.

CD7767198B3A43B2BED34A8DDA1603CF.description:
Construct an argument that plants and
animals have internal and external structures that
function to support survival, growth, behavior and
reproduction.
[Clarification Statement: Examples of structures could
include thorns, stems, roots, colored petals, heart,
stomach, lung, brain, and skin.]

14BA3A4364BC45DFBBF81FC51F918537.description: LIFE SCIENCES: From Molecules to Organisms: Structures and Processes

342BBA98F9E44303B8E6A23EE2718D72.description:
Identify the relationships between the
roles of science, technology, and
Catholic ethics in a global community.

8B7B266B12084BA7809CF71BC413B35F.description:
Work cooperatively and respect my
classmates’ ideas, roles, and abilities.

2C864FE7B89F439DBD693CA93D00F595.description:
Compare multiple solutions to
transferring information.

EFB6C73FC3D24302ACE8B3EC639DB6CC.description:
Create a pattern to transfer
information.

4393E10AE531498DAE4E4FC1C4EC280F.description:
High-tech devices, such as computers or cell
phones, can receive and decode information—
convert it from digitized form to voice—and vice
versa.

0ECB41E5F9C34B17957668AB9947C192.description:
Digitized information can be transmitted over
long distances without significant degradation.

EB8E690D69D5431698A312B599727311.description:
Generate and compare multiple solutions that
use patterns to transfer information.
[Clarification Statement: Examples of solutions could
include drums sending coded information through sound
waves, using a grid of ones and zeros representing black
and white to send information about a picture and using
morse code to send text.]

565A559C131E43278C0EFC0B41B185A2.description:
Model that light needs to be reflected
from an object to be seen.

3142056FA40241778484915C4C76C932.description:
Distinguish that light travels in straight
paths.

748162E72EF84A92AEDAE61435B606DD.description:
An object can be seen when light reflected from it
surface enters the eyes.

C433CB0B5C544F3B97A2E94F91B64837.description:
Develop a model to describe that light reflecting
from objects and entering the eye allows objects to be
seen.
[Assessment Boundary: Assessment does not include
knowledge of specific colors reflected and seen, the
cellular mechanisms of vision, or how the retina works.]

6EC647FA2C9A46309FEA35EEFFECC09F.description:
Identify the difference between a high
energy and low energy wave by
applying the terms amplitude and
wavelength.

6053B79A02EE4287AADF6713587F8048.description:
Model a high energy wave and a low
energy wave.

53202F76F7E14E27B4DDE9DA52E94CB7.description:
Recognize the relationship between
energy, frequency, and wavelength.

DAF5CAAF329942519681B28EE1BBB89E.description:
Waves of the same type can differ in amplitude
(height of the wave) and wavelength (spacing
between wave peaks).

310EB29298C3462C973604CAAAF23A68.description: Waves are regular patterns of motion.

B9DCEE5049294B198DFAFAF1E770F81C.description:
Develop a model of waves to describe patterns in
terms of amplitude and wavelength and that waves can
cause objects to move.
[Clarification Statement: Examples of models could include
diagrams, analogies, and physical models using wire to
illustrate wavelength and amplitude of waves. Assessment
Boundary: Assessment does not include interference
effects, electromagnetic waves, non periodic waves, or
quantitative models of amplitude and wavelength.]

A16F3D6096C94F39ABDE64F8D52E33EE.description: PHYSICAL SCIENCE: Waves and their Applications in Technologies for Information Transfer

C4705032AB234DE5B45DEE463BAF2326.description:
Design a device that converts energy
from one form to another.

CBDE61CF9A2A4CD69473C96E4492AAEB.description:
Recognize that energy can be
converted from one form to another.

7BB35D4F1C0D4F7484C87A300071361A.description:
Energy can also be transferred from place to place
by electric currents, which can then be used locally
to produce motion, sound, heat, or light. The
currents may have been produced to begin with
by transforming the energy of motion into
electrical energy.

E8B3228E6FE8450FA4DEDAFA2EE1C9DB.description: Light also transfers energy from place to place.

EB618BD7AB2E4F68908815B9AA80FF24.description:
Energy is present whenever there are moving
objects, sound, light, or heat.

83CB559BEBF545A9945CBB905A72A8A7.description:
Apply scientific ideas to design, test, and refine a
device that converts energy from one form to another.
[Clarification Statement: examples of devices could
include electric circuits that convert electrical energy into
motion energy of a vehicle, light, or sound; and, a passive
solar heater that converts light into heat. Examples of
constraints could include materials, cost, or time to design
a device. Assessment Boundary: devices should be limited to those that convert motion energy to electric energy or
used stored energy to cause motion or produce light or
sound.]

64A06CBBF4264367970F4801BECC0EFB.description:
Identify the cause and effect
relationship between the strength of a
force and an object.

5E73FC6DF89E420D80DD84F41C7363F4.description:
Generate questions about how energy
transfers when objects collide.

4B35FDD8CF8C4D25AB7AC39413520467.description:
Predict the change in energy when two
objects collide.

21652BE01E3B4439BC04025D0EA1EEC1.description:
In such collisions, some energy is typically also
transferred to the surrounding air; as a result, the
air gets heated and sound is produced.

87808B4EB80D422780239709EE41EE05.description:
When objects collide, energy can be transferred
from one object to another, thereby changing
their motion.

70538C1428D44B6883A6C735904B7635.description:
Ask questions and predict outcomes about the
changes in energy that occur when objects collide.
[Clarification Statement: Emphasis is on the change in
energy due to the change in speed not on the forces as
objects interact. Assessment boundary: assessment does
not include quantitative measurements of energy]

D1CE3383996A4D7D8ACDB88425A1FE85.description:
Investigate how sound, light, heat, and
electricity are transferred.

D47B638E4A944B408A948DAC5B1D6451.description:
Plan and carry out investigations to
demonstrate how energy can be
transferred from place to place.

CD29018A370F43038F66A2FD6A63630D.description:
Energy can be moved from place to place by
moving objects or through sound, light, heat, or
electric currents.

08BC3DE408E64809A5EBB3F3259FFE0A.description:
Make observations to provide evidence that
energy can be transferred from place to place by sound,
light, heat, and electric currents.
[Assessment Boundary: Does not include quantitative
measurements of energy]

A29CE4B1620448D7A0CFBE5399EC9AA8.description:
Demonstrate that an object with more
speed has greater energy than an
object moving at a slower speed.

47BAD50E8B854BC29DA115103EFDA5F5.description:
Investigate the relationship between
speed and energy through
experimentation.

7D87D3621FE8414F9FA406CAEE79F94F.description:
The faster a given object is moving, the more
energy it possesses.

AC5B439C1FC54E59B24C37A7E769BC99.description:
Use evidence to construct an explanation relating
the speed of an object to the energy of that object.
[Assessment Boundary: Assessment does not include
quantitative measures or changes in speed of an object or
on any precise or quantitative definition of energy.]
